  "Idea": "We propose 'Linguistically-Grounded Counterfactual Probing for Adversarial Robustness in NMT' (LC-PAR), a novel framework that evaluates the adversarial sensitivity of Neural Machine Translation systems without relying on ground-truth translations by leveraging linguistically-informed counterfactual interventions and entailment coherence tracking. Instead of constructing a global semantic manifold, LC-PAR performs localized, syntax-driven perturbations (e.g., negation insertion, quantifier shifting, voice alternation, coreference redirection) guided by universal grammatical principles. For each original sentence, we generate a set of minimally modified counterfactuals that preserve factual meaning but alter surface realization in semantically constrained ways. These are processed through the NMT encoder, and their contextual representations are compared using a frozen, high-precision Natural Language Inference (NLI) model to assess whether the system maintains logical equivalence between original and perturbed inputs. Crucially, we do not require access to the translation output. Instead, we measure the degradation in bidirectional entailment scores (i.e., how well the model's encoded representation of the perturbed input entails the original and vice versa) as a proxy for semantic fragility. To enhance diagnostic precision, we annotate each perturbation type with its linguistic category and compute per-class sensitivity scores, enabling fine-grained analysis of architectural weaknesses (e.g., 'Transformer models exhibit 40% higher inconsistency on negation flips than on passive-to-active conversions'). We further introduce a reconstruction fidelity check: translating source → target → back-projected source using pivot decoding, then evaluating whether the reconstructed source maintains entailment symmetry with the original in the same NLI space. This creates a closed-loop, reference-free robustness metric that is both interpretable and scalable. The significance of LC-PAR lies in its ability to move beyond aggregate robustness scores and expose *structured vulnerabilities* tied to specific linguistic phenomena. By grounding evaluation in formal linguistic categories, it offers model developers actionable feedback for targeted robustification. Potential impact includes integration into NMT development pipelines, use in regulatory assessments of multilingual AI safety, and extension to other sequence-to-sequence tasks like summarization or dialogue.",
